The '''Commercial Standard Digital Bus''' ('''CSDB''') is a unidirectional [[asynchronous bus]], formerly known as the '''Collins Standard Digital Bus'''. The maximum speed is 50 kbit/s.

It is used on most buses in NSW.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}

Most civilian aircraft use one of 3 serial buses: the Commercial Standard Digital Bus (CSDB),<ref>
Cary Spitzer.
"The Avionics Handbook".
Lee Harrison.
[http://www.davi.ws/avionics/TheAvionicsHandbook_Cap_3.pdf Chapter 3: Commercial Standard Digital Bus]
</ref>
ARINC 429, or AS-15531.

The Commercial Standard Digital Bus is a two-wire [[asynchronous communication|asynchronous]] broadcast [[data transmission]] bus. Data is transmitted over an interconnecting cable by devices that comply with [[Electronic Industries Association]] (EIA) [[EIA-422|RS-422A]].
The physical layer is [[EIA-422]].<ref name="interfacebus" />

Messages on the CSDB consist of one address byte followed by any number of data bytes.<ref name="interfacebus" >
[http://www.interfacebus.com/Avionics_CSDB_Interface_Description.html "Commercial Standard Communications Bus"].
</ref>

